# React Component Conventions

## Folder Structure

Every component lives in its own folder:

```
ComponentName/
  ComponentName.tsx
  ComponentName.module.css
  ComponentName.test.tsx
  index.ts
```

- `index.ts` re-exports the component as a named export.
- CSS Module file is required for any component with styles.
- Test file colocated in the same folder.

## Styling

- Use CSS Modules (`*.module.css`) for all component styles.
- No global CSS files. No inline styles except for dynamic computed values.
- Class composition via the `cx()` helper or template literals.

## State Management

- Use zustand stores over prop drilling. Maximum 5-6 props per component.
- Use `useShallow` from `zustand/react/shallow` for object/array selectors.
- Create facade hooks (e.g. `useAuth()`, `useFeed()`) for common store access patterns.
- No React Context for shared state. Use zustand stores instead.
- Keep form/modal state local with `useState` or `useReducer`.

## Component Design

- Extract sub-components when JSX exceeds 50 lines of markup.
- Prefer composition over long conditional rendering chains.
- Use `memo()` only when profiling shows actual re-render issues.
- Colocate single-use hooks with their component; shared hooks go in `hooks/`.

## Naming Conventions

- Event handler props: `onX` (e.g. `onClick`, `onSubmit`).
- Internal event handlers: `handleX` (e.g. `handleClick`, `handleSubmit`).
- Boolean props: `isX` or `hasX` (e.g. `isLoading`, `hasError`).
- Hooks: `useX` (e.g. `useAuth`, `useChatStream`).

## Testing

- Every component with business logic has a colocated `.test.tsx` file.
- Test user-visible behavior, not implementation details.
- Use `@testing-library/react` with `renderWithProviders` from `test/render.tsx`.
- Mock API calls via `vi.mock`; mock stores via `test/store-helpers.ts`.
